Basic Parser

Queries are designed to process, filter, and summarize data effectively.
Specifically, queries allow you to:
- Filter out irrelevant data
- Select specific components of the data to view
- Group, summarize, and calculate metrics on the data

You can construct queries progressively. Here are examples of how to build them:

1. Simple Filtering
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}	filter not c.job icontains .Software
	Explanation: Filters all rows where the `job` column does not contain `Software`.
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}	filter not p.SUMMARY icontains .Report
	Explanation: Filters all events without a SUMMARY containing 'Report'.
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}	filter not h.user-agent icontains .Kmail
	Explanation: Filters all emails sent with a user agent that does not contain `kmail`.
{{end -}}

2. Selecting Components (Tabular Conversion)
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}	into table c.job f.year[c.startdate] f.month[c.startdate]
	Explanation: This extracts specific fields from the rows and converts them into a tabular format for viewing.
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}	into table p.LOCATION f.year[p.DUE] f.month[p.DUE]
	Explanation: This extracts specific fields from the events and converts them into a tabular format for viewing.
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}	into table h.user-agent h.subject f.year[h.date] f.month[h.date]
	Explanation: This extracts specific fields from the emails and converts them into a tabular format for viewing.
{{end -}}

3. Grouping and Summarization
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}	into summary c.job calculate f.sum[c.pay] f.count
	Explanation: This groups the rows based on specific fields, and then applies aggregate calculations (like sums or counts) to those groups.
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}	into summary p.LOCATION f.year[p.DUE] f.month[p.DUE] calculate f.count
	Explanation: This groups the events based on specific fields, and then applies aggregate calculations (like sums or counts) to those groups.
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}	into summary h.user-agent h.subject f.year[h.date] f.month[h.date] calculate f.sum[c.size] f.count
	Explanation: This groups the emails based on specific fields, and then applies aggregate calculations (like sums or counts) to those groups.
{{end -}}

4. Sorting Data
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}	sort f.year[c.startdate] f.month[c.startdate]
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}	sort f.year[p.DUE] f.month[p.DUE]
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}	sort f.year[h.date] f.month[h.date]
{{end -}}
	Explanation: This sorts the resulting data based on the specified fields.

5. Combining Operations
	Operations can be chained together sequentially to achieve complex data processing:
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}	filter c.startdate icontains .Software into summary c.job f.year[c.startdate] calculate f.count filter c.year-startdate eq 2022 sort c.job
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}	filter p.SUMMARY icontains .Report into summary p.LOCATION f.year[p.DUE] f.month[p.DUE] calculate f.count filter c.year-DUE eq 2022 sort p.LOCATION
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}	filter h.user-agent icontains .Kmail into summary h.user-agent f.year[h.date] calculate f.count filter c.year-date eq 2022 sort h.user-agent
{{end -}}

Notes:
- String literals consisting of a single word should begin with a dot (`.`).
{{if eq .Type "csv"}}- Columns are referred to by `c.`.
{{else if eq .Type "ical"}}- Properties are referred to with `p.`. Once in table form, they become columns referred to by `c.`.
- Subcomponents are not fully implemented yet.
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}- Headers are referred to with `h.`. Once in table form, they become columns referred to by `c.`.
- Body parsing components are not fully implemented yet.
{{end -}}
- All functions must be preceded by `f.`.
- Extension PRs are welcome and encouraged!
{{if eq .Type "ical"}}- Once converted to table form, the data cannot be converted back to ical / ics.
{{else if eq .Type "mail"}}- Once converted to table form, the data cannot be converted back to mailfile or mbox.
{{end -}}
